    <rdfs:comment xml:lang="ja">康 僧会（こう そうえ、? - 280年）は、中国・三国呉の訳経僧である。康居の出身。</rdfs:comment>
    <rdfs:comment xml:lang="zh">康僧会（？－280年），号超化禅师，康居人，三国时期著名佛教高僧，翻译师。 早年丧双亲，服丧后出家，从学于南阳韩林、颍川皮业、会稽陈慧等高僧，学习汉译佛典。三国东吴赤乌十年（247年）设道场并教化世人，因其相貌异常，吴主孙权请之，后被感化并皈依，为之建立建初寺。梵呗也于此时传入中国。晋太康元年圆寂。译经有《吴品经》、《杂譬喻经》、《六度集经》等。</rdfs:comment>
    <rdfs:comment xml:lang="en">Kang Senghui (traditional: 康僧會; simplified: 康僧会; pinyin: Kāng Sēnghuì; Wade-Giles: K&#39;ang Seng-hui; died 280) was a Buddhist monk and translator during the Three Kingdoms period of ancient China. He was born in Jiaozhi (Chinese 交趾; modern-day northern Vietnam), in the extreme south of the Chinese empire. He was the son of a Sogdian merchant. Kang contributed to the diffusion and translation of Buddhist sutras into the Chinese language. According to legend the first Buddha relic in China appeared in a vase in 248 C.E. so that Kang Senghui would have something to show a local ruler.  The king of Wu Sun Quan would unsuccessfully attempt to destroy the tooth, by subjecting it to various tests.</rdfs:comment>
    <rdfs:comment xml:lang="pl">Kang Senghui (data urodzenia nieznana; zm. 280); chiń. upr.: 康僧会; chiń. trad.: 康僧會; pinyin: Kāng Sēnghui; wiet. Khương Tăng Hội; kor. Kang Sŭnghoe (강승회); jap. Kōsōkai – buddysta wietnamski i chiński, jedna z ważnych postaci wczesnego okresu rozwoju buddyzmu w Chinach, prekursor szkół thiền i chan.</rdfs:comment>
    <rdfs:comment xml:lang="it">Kāng Sēnghuì (Sēnghuì il Sogdiano), era originario della zona del Tonchino (Giao Chỉ, cin. 交趾 Jiāozhǐ), probabilmente proveniva da Hanoi, ma la sua famiglia, di origine sogdiana, proveniva dall&#39;India dove si era stabilita da alcune generazioni, trasferendosi quindi ad Hanoi dove svolsero l&#39;attività di mercanti per, successivamente, migrare in Cina. Non rimane molto delle sue opere di traduzione se non degli Avadāna (o Jatāka), novantuno per l&#39;esattezza, tradotti nel 251 e riportati nel 六度集經 (Liùdùjí jīng giapp. Rokudojū kyō, &quot;Sutra sulla Raccolta delle sei perfezioni&quot;, conservato al T.D. 152).</rdfs:comment>
